# Agent skills and capabilities (canon)

Living document: edit under `canon/rules/`.

## Terminal and execution

- You may run `go build`, `go test`, `pytest`, and `npm run build` when they help validate changes.
- On compile or test failures, read the log, fix the code, and re-run until green (within reasonable scope of the task).

## Codebase indexing

- Use **@Codebase** (or equivalent broad search) to map relationships between Go services, Python scripts, and React components before invasive edits.
- Index **`go.mod`**, **`package.json`**, and **`requirements.txt`** (or lockfiles) so dependency claims match the repo.

## Database and schema

- Use available SQL / DB tooling to inspect real schemas when writing data access code.
- Match **exact** column names and types from existing metadata or migrations—do not invent columns.

## Documentation and web

- Use **@Docs** (or MCP docs tools) for up-to-date references for React, Go, and .NET when the stack requires it.
- If library syntax or breaking changes are uncertain for current-year releases, verify with **web search** before asserting APIs.

## Security audit (mandatory before handoff)

- After substantive code generation, run a quick **security pass** aligned with **OWASP Top 10** thinking (injection, broken access control, XSS, sensitive data exposure, etc.).
- Fix obvious issues in the same change set; call out residual risks explicitly if they need human review.
